name: ‚àû Clear Autism ‚àû
content:
Individual preference should be respected, of course, but if you don't know for sure what that is, defaulting to IFL is quite simply the polite and respectful thing to do, even if you don't understand or agree with it - if you really want to put the person first, that is.
#Autism

name: ‚àû Clear Autism ‚àû
content:
If we say a person IS +adjective we're referring to an innate quality - she is lefthanded, we are French, they are trans. It's an intrinsic part of the person.
This is why most autistic people have a clear preference for IFL rather than PFL. Autism is a fundamental part of them.

name: ‚àû Clear Autism ‚àû
content: In English, when we say a person HAS +noun, we're usually either talking about illness, which is problematic in the case of autism, or referring to an externally observable attribute - he has long hair, I have brown eyes, etc. Autism isn't observable, so we're observing behaviour

content:
Red Flag 10

There are a lot of colors and visual chaos everywhere.

This can be observed especially commonly in educational spaces (preschool, school, etc.)

Spaces designed like this are NOT autistic friendly and it shows a lack of basic autism understanding.

(11/?)

name: autistictic - #EndAutmisiaNow #StopTheShock
content:
Red Flag 9

Staff use harmful autism language.

This is taught in non-autistic led autism environments.

It means staff didn‚Äòt get autistic-led training and adopted harmful views.

E.g. ‚Äûwith autism‚Äú, ‚Äûsuffer from autism‚Äú, ‚Äûsymptoms of autism‚Äú, ‚Äûchallenging behavior‚Äú.

(10/?)

name: autistictic - #EndAutmisiaNow #StopTheShock
content:
Red Flag 8

No/little use of sensory accommodations.

Yes, every autistic has different sensory needs.

But if you‚Äôre in an ‚Äûautism space‚Äú and don‚Äòt REGULARLY see ear defenders, sunglasses, stim tools, etc. it‚Äòs a sign that autistic needs aren‚Äòt accommodated by default.

(9/?)

name: autistictic - #EndAutmisiaNow #StopTheShock
content:
Red Flag 6

No use or problematic use of AAC.

Augmentative and Alternative Communication is anything that isn‚Äòt oral speech (e.g. speech output devices, picture cards).

If AAC use is not accepted, encouraged, normal in an autism space, that space is not doing it right.

(7/?)

name: autistictic - #EndAutmisiaNow #StopTheShock
content:
Red Flag 1

It‚Äòs non-autistic led.

Being non-autistic led is a huge red flag and sadly one you will likely spot in MOST autism spaces.

Being non-autistic led likely means lots of harmful views and practices exist and that you‚Äòre likely to spot the following red flags.
